column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

Cattle numbers eased to 393 head, back approximately 100 on last week. Quality ranged from plain to very good in a typical winter offering. Cow numbers were back with young cattle making up 75% of the yarding. Numbers were made up of 275 young cattle, 94 cows, 22 grown bulls and a few open auction young cattle. Several pens of grain assisted young cattle were offered selling to 428c/kg for a good result. Yearlings and vealers sold mostly to feeders a few cents either side of last weeks levels. Grown steers sold to 5c/kg stronger with grown heifers selling around firm. The best heavy cows sold similar making to 354c and bulls were 30c to 40c/kg easier. 

Yearlings sold to the trade from 355c to 428c and to feeders from 310c to 401c, plainer types sold from 250c to 292c/kg. 

Light and medium weight steers sold from 360c to 400c, with heavy weights selling from 372c to 380c, feeders paid from 302c to 401c/kg. Medium weight grown heifers sold to 230c, with heavier weights selling from 248c to 358c. Feeders and restockerâ€™s paid to 204c for plainer types. Light weight cows sold to 140c, Medium weight 1 and 2 scores sold from 196c to 282c. Heavy 3 and 4 score cows sold from 322c to 354c with the 1 and 2 scores selling from 224c to 320c/kg. Medium weight bulls sold from 280c to 284c, heavy weights sold from 220c to 288c, feeders paid from 242 to 355c for young bulls. 

Market Reporter - Graham Pymer.
